<br>
All this invention does is detect a shift in the center of gravity of whatever is on it.  If you put a bucket of water and made waves in it the thing would move because it would sense the weight going from one side to another.<br>
<br>
This isn't anywhere near AI or operating complex machinery.  I can't even see detecting a shift in weight developing into either one of these things.<br>
<br>
But again it is a great breakthrough to make it do what it does with no engine and only a small amount of electricity. <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#112512><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub16.ezboard.com/unewwenrunemaster.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Newwen Runemaster</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Druzzil Ro Member</span><br>  Posts: 124<br> <font color=#CCCCC8>(12/7/01 6:48:27 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub16.ezboard.com/fdruzzilro86846frm10.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=104.topic&index=10>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ginger = Lame</span><hr size=1> pressure= movement<br>
